<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7091> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7091" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "See now Degrassi's comments on ILLRP 1274a and in Acta of the 5th Internat. Congress of Gr. and Lat. Epig., 155. A sarcophagus found in Rome at the Via Cristophoro Colombo and now in the Epigraphical Museum of the Capitoline Museum bears the inscription in early letters P. Cornelio P. f. Scapola pontfex (sic) max. This person is otherwise unknown, nor has the inscription been fully published. Degrassi notes that this inscription confirms that the Scapula known from Fast. Cap. as mag. eq. in 362 (MRR 2.118) may be a Cornelius, and supports the reading in Liv. 8.22.1, P. Cornelio Scapula, for the name of the consul of 328 (MRR 2.145; RE no. 316, cf. 315). See AEpig. 1967, no. 19, and J. M. Reynolds, JRS 61, 1971, 138-139. See now H. Blanck, Zwei Corneliersarcophage, MDAI(R) 73-74, 1968, 72-77.\n" ;
	dprr:hasID 7091 .
